# The Ledger — Build Workflow & Quality Standard

## Quality standard

"Does it build" is the floor, not the bar. Every change must meet:
- Correct data (no fabricated facts presented as real)
- Correct sourcing (tier values, dates, and links visible in UI)
- Correct rendering (SSR for all route pages — see below)
- No regressions (build passes, existing features still work)
- Honest empty states (no fabricated fill-ins when data is missing)

## Architecture rule — SSR on all route pages

**Route pages (`app/**/page.tsx`) must be server components.** Do not add `'use client'` to a route page file. Interactive sub-components (tabs, accordions, charts) use `'use client'` — the route page itself does not.

Why: crawlers index server-rendered HTML. A `'use client'` route page is invisible to Google. The product goal is to be the best political research resource — that requires search visibility.

Current violation: `app/politicians/[id]/page.tsx` is `'use client'`. This must be converted to a server component shell with client sub-components in a future phase.

## Branch workflow

- All work on `phase-5-national-wiring` or a named feature branch — **never directly on `main`**
- Commit after each completed task before starting the next
- `npm run build` must pass before any commit
- Do not merge to `main` without explicit owner instruction

## Phase gates

Stop and wait for owner review after each phase:
1. Commit completed work to the branch
2. Run `npm run build` — report pass/fail
3. Report: what was changed, what was tested, what was NOT changed
4. Do not start the next phase until the owner confirms

Report format (3 lines max):
```
Build: pass | fail
Files changed: [list]
Verified: [what you actually tested]
```

## Data change discipline

- Never launch parallel agents editing the same data files — causes regressions
- After data changes, run: `npm run sync:legislators` then `npm run verify:office`
- Build must pass: `npm run build`
- Owner runs `npm run dev` in their own terminal — do not start dev servers

## Scope discipline

- Do not add features, refactor, or introduce abstractions beyond what the task requires
- Do not add error handling for scenarios that cannot happen
- Do not write comments that explain WHAT the code does — only WHY when non-obvious
- Scope creep (adding unrequested components, changing copy, renaming things) is a task failure

## When to stop and ask

Stop and ask the owner only for:
- Scope changes (adding features not in the brief)
- Credibility tradeoffs (which source to trust when records conflict)
- Major UX direction changes

Do not stop and ask for routine implementation decisions.

## Mock data rules

- Mock data pages (`/lobbying`, `/elections`) must carry a visible "Demo — not verified" banner until replaced by real data pipelines
- Never silently present demo data as if it were official
- `demoTradeCount` in stock trades must be visible to the user — not just tracked in code

## Sync script commands

```bash
npm run sync:legislators      # refresh congressional roster
npm run sync:fec-national     # FEC finance for all 537 members
npm run sync:congress-votes   # roll-call votes
npm run sync:stock-trades     # STOCK Act PTR trades
npm run sync:news-national    # GDELT news for all members
npm run verify:office         # confirm office resolution is clean
npm run build                 # must pass before any commit
```
